---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
import Figure from '../components/Figure.astro';
import PartHeader from '../components/PartHeader.astro';
import ContactPatchDiagram from '../components/ContactPatchDiagram.astro';
import WeightTransferDiagram from '../components/WeightTransferDiagram.astro';
import CornerDiagram from '../components/CornerDiagram.astro';
import SideNote from '../components/SideNote.astro';
import Math from '../components/Math.astro';
import TractionBudget from '../components/TractionBudget.svelte';
import CorneringPhases from '../components/CorneringPhases.svelte';
import LeanFactors from '../components/LeanFactors.svelte';

const toc = [
  { part: 'I', name: 'The Model', href: '#p1', items: [
    ['01', 'The Tyre & Contact Patch', '#s-patch'],
    ['02', 'The Traction Budget', '#s-grip'],
    ['03', 'Vision & Where to Look', '#s-vision'],
  ]},
  { part: 'II', name: 'The Inputs', href: '#p2', items: [
    ['04', 'Counter-steering', '#s-counter'],
    ['05', 'Braking & Trail-braking', '#s-brake'],
    ['06', 'Throttle', '#s-throttle'],
    ['07', 'Gear Changes', '#s-gears'],
    ['08', 'Leaning', '#s-lean'],
    ['09', 'Body Position', '#s-body'],
    ['10', 'Making the Bike Lean Quickly', '#s-turnin'],
  ]},
  { part: 'III', name: 'The Path', href: '#p3', items: [
    ['11', 'Race Lines', '#s-lines'],
  ]},
  { part: 'IV', name: 'Putting It Together', href: '#p4', items: [
    ['12', 'Cornering: Entry · Apex · Exit', '#s-corner'],
  ]},
];
---

<Layout>
  <main class="mx-auto max-w-[80rem] px-4">
    <div class="paper">
    <!-- ── Hero / Preface ─────────────────────────────── -->
    <section class="pt-14 pb-10 border-b border-[var(--color-rule)]">
      <div class="label mb-3">Preface</div>
      <h1 class="text-3xl sm:text-4xl leading-tight">
        How to Corner Fast,<br />and Why It Works.
      </h1>
      <p class="prose-manual mt-4">
        We build the manual in four parts. The first is the model: how much grip a tyre
        really has, and how every input spends it. The second is the inputs themselves:
        brakes, throttle, steering, gears, and our own body. The third is the line we
        choose through a corner. The fourth is the corner itself, where all of it happens
        at once. The figures are interactive; push on them. The maths sits beside the
        words in layers, so you can read the plain idea and stop, or keep opening it until
        you reach the full model.
      </p>

      <!-- grouped contents -->
      <nav class="mt-8 grid sm:grid-cols-2 gap-x-10 gap-y-6">
        {toc.map((p) => (
          <div>
            <a href={p.href} class="part-kicker block mb-2 hover:underline">
              Part {p.part} · {p.name}
            </a>
            <ul class="space-y-1">
              {p.items.map(([num, name, href]) => (
                <li>
                  <a href={href} class="group flex items-baseline gap-2 py-0.5">
                    <span class="section-num text-xs">{num}</span>
                    <span class="font-mono text-sm text-[var(--color-ink-soft)] group-hover:text-[var(--color-ink)]">{name}</span>
                  </a>
                </li>
              ))}
            </ul>
          </div>
        ))}
      </nav>
    </section>

    <!-- ══════════════════ PART I ══════════════════ -->
    <PartHeader
      id="p1" part="I" title="The Model"
      plate="I" plateTitle="Contact Patch"
      intro="Three things govern everything that follows: the small contact patch that is our only link to the road, the grip it can give, and where we point our eyes. Get these right and every input later becomes obvious; get them wrong and no amount of technique will save us."
    >
      <ContactPatchDiagram />
    </PartHeader>

    <!-- 01 Contact Patch -->
    <section id="s-patch" class="py-9 border-b border-[var(--color-rule)] scroll-mt-16">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-2">
        <span class="label">Section 01</span><span class="tag">Draft</span>
      </div>
      <h3 class="text-xl mb-4">The Tyre &amp; Contact Patch</h3>
      <div class="prose-manual">
        <p>
            Everything we ask of the bike runs through two small patches of rubber: one
            at the front, one at the rear, each about the size of a palm. That is our
            entire connection to the road, and our entire budget of grip;
            every input we make is a withdrawal from it.
          </p>
          <p>
            Grip changes constantly. It rises and falls with the load
            pressing the tyre down, with its temperature, and with the
            surface beneath us; a cold tyre gives up far less than a warm
            one, which is why we bring them up to temperature before we lean on them.
          </p>
          <p>
            The patch is at its biggest when the bike stands upright. As we lean, we roll
            onto the rounded shoulder of the tyre and the patch grows smaller. That is the
            real cost of lean angle: it quietly shrinks the very thing we are spending.
          </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- 02 Traction Budget -->
    <section id="s-grip" class="py-9 border-b border-[var(--color-rule)] scroll-mt-16">
      <div class="label mb-2">Section 02</div>
      <h3 class="text-xl mb-4">The Traction Budget</h3>

      <div class="prose-manual">
        <p>
          A tyre has one budget of grip, shared between slowing or driving
          (longitudinal) and turning (lateral).<SideNote marker="1">Longitudinal grip is what we spend on brake and throttle; lateral grip is what we spend on lean. One budget feeds both.</SideNote>
          Spend it all in one direction and there is none left for the other.
        </p>

        <h4 class="idea-kicker">The basic idea: a friction circle</h4>
        <p>
          Treat the limit as the same in every direction: a circle of radius
          <Math expr={String.raw`F_{\max}=\mu F_z`} />. The longitudinal demand
          <Math expr={String.raw`F_x`} /> and lateral demand <Math expr={String.raw`F_y`} />
          add as a vector, and the resultant cannot leave the circle:
        </p>
        <Math display expr={String.raw`\left(\frac{F_x}{F_{\max}}\right)^2 + \left(\frac{F_y}{F_{\max}}\right)^2 \le 1`} />
        <p>
          So 70% brake with 70% lean is fine: <Math expr={String.raw`0.7^2 + 0.7^2 = 0.98 \le 1`} />,
          just inside the limit. Drag the node below and feel the trade-off.<SideNote marker="2">The circle is Pacejka's idealisation; real tyres trace a slightly taller <em>ellipse</em> (Pacejka 2006; Foale 2006).</SideNote>
        </p>
      </div>

      <Figure num="2.1" title="The Friction Circle">
        <TractionBudget client:visible initialMode="circle" showModes={false} />
      </Figure>

      <div class="prose-manual">
        <h4 class="idea-kicker">Adding real tyre behaviour</h4>
        <p>
          Real tyres are not isotropic, so the circle is really an ellipse;
          longitudinal and lateral peak grip differ:
        </p>
        <Math display expr={String.raw`\left(\frac{F_x}{F_{x,\max}}\right)^2 + \left(\frac{F_y}{F_{y,\max}}\right)^2 \le 1`} />
        <p>
          And grip is load-sensitive: the friction coefficient falls as
          vertical load rises (Milliken &amp; Milliken, Fig. 2.9), so the whole budget breathes
          with weight transfer:
        </p>
        <Math display expr={String.raw`\mu(F_z) = \mu_0 - k\,F_z, \qquad k > 0`} />
        <p>
          Peak force <Math expr={String.raw`F_{\max}=\mu(F_z)\,F_z`} /> still grows with load,
          but at a diminishing rate. A leaned tyre also makes lateral force from
          camber thrust as well as slip, so lean angle
          <Math expr={String.raw`\gamma`} /> contributes directly:
          <Math expr={String.raw`F_y \approx C_\alpha\,\alpha + C_\gamma\,\gamma`} />. Raise the
          load below and watch the ellipse breathe.
        </p>
      </div>

      <Figure num="2.2" title="The Friction Ellipse: Load Sensitivity">
        <TractionBudget client:visible initialMode="ellipse" showModes={false} />
      </Figure>

      <div class="prose-manual">
        <h4 class="idea-kicker">What's actually happening</h4>
        <p>
          Tyre force is a nonlinear function of slip ratio <Math expr={String.raw`\kappa`} /> and
          slip angle <Math expr={String.raw`\alpha`} />, captured by Pacejka's Magic Formula:
        </p>
        <Math display expr={String.raw`F = F_z\,D\,\sin\!\Big(C\arctan\!\big(Bs - E(Bs - \arctan Bs)\big)\Big)`} />
        <p>
          Under combined slip the two forces interact, bending the ellipse.
          Meanwhile each tyre's load is set dynamically by acceleration and centre-of-mass height; under braking, the front is loaded:
        </p>
        <Math display expr={String.raw`F_{z,\text{front}} = \frac{m g\,b - m\,a_x\,h}{L}, \qquad \Delta F_z = \frac{m\,a_x\,h}{L}`} />
        <p>
          So the &ldquo;friction circle&rdquo; is really a load- and slip-dependent
          surface in <Math expr={String.raw`(\kappa,\ \alpha,\ F_z,\ \gamma)`} />
          space, changing every instant of the corner. Brake hard below and watch the front
          ellipse grow.
        </p>
      </div>

      <Figure num="2.3" title="Combined Slip &amp; Load Transfer">
        <TractionBudget client:visible initialMode="combined" showModes={false} />
      </Figure>

      <div class="refs">
        <div class="label" style="margin-bottom:0.4rem;">References · §02</div>
        <ol class="ref-list">
          <li>Pacejka, H. B. (2006). <em>Tire and Vehicle Dynamics</em> (2nd ed.). SAE. friction circle/ellipse; Magic Formula; combined slip.</li>
          <li>Milliken, W. F. &amp; Milliken, D. L. (1995). <em>Race Car Vehicle Dynamics</em>. SAE. tyre load sensitivity (Fig. 2.9 dataset).</li>
          <li>Cossalter, V. (2006). <em>Motorcycle Dynamics</em> (2nd ed.). motorcycle friction ellipse; camber thrust.</li>
          <li>Foale, T. (2006). <em>Motorcycle Handling and Chassis Design</em> (2nd ed.).</li>
          <li>Wong, J. Y. (2008). <em>Theory of Ground Vehicles</em> (2nd ed.). Wiley.</li>
        </ol>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- 03 Vision -->
    <section id="s-vision" class="py-9 border-b border-[var(--color-rule)] scroll-mt-16">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-2">
        <span class="label">Section 03</span><span class="tag">Draft</span>
      </div>
      <h3 class="text-xl mb-4">Vision &amp; Where to Look</h3>
      <div class="prose-manual">
          <p>
            We go where we look; the bike follows our eyes. Stare at the thing that
            frightens us and we drift straight into it; that is target fixation. So we keep
            our eyes up, and we look through the corner to where we want to be next: the
            turn-in, then the apex, then the exit. Peripheral vision handles the rest.
          </p>
          <p>
            This is what saves us when we run wide. The rider who runs wide and crashes is
            usually staring at the edge of the road, right where they are afraid of going.
            Lift the eyes to the exit and the bike follows them back. The moment the corner
            tightens and the edge looms is exactly when we are tempted to panic and shut the
            throttle (§06); it is also exactly the moment to look up.
          </p>
        </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ══════════════════ PART II ══════════════════ -->
    <PartHeader
      id="p2" part="II" title="The Inputs"
      plate="II" plateTitle="Weight Transfer"
      intro="Every control spends from the one budget of grip: the bars, the brakes, the throttle, the gears, and our own body. In the right order and measure, each input hands off to the next without a gap. Rush them or overlap them badly and we overspend; the tyre lets go."
    >
      <WeightTransferDiagram />
    </PartHeader>

    <!-- 04 Counter-steering -->
    <section id="s-counter" class="py-9 border-b border-[var(--color-rule)] scroll-mt-16">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-2">
        <span class="label">Section 04</span><span class="tag">Draft</span>
      </div>
      <h3 class="text-xl mb-4">Counter-steering</h3>
      <div class="prose-manual">
          <p>
            Above walking pace, we lean the bike by pushing on the bars. To go right, we
            press forward on the right bar; the bike rolls to the right and the turn begins.
            It feels backwards the first time, and it works every time.
          </p>
          <p>
            What happens underneath is simple. That small steer slides the contact patches
            out to the side, out from under our combined weight, and the bike falls into the
            lean we asked for. To stand it back up, we ease the pressure off, or push gently
            the other way. This is how every lean begins, whether we name it or not;
            everything in Making the Bike Lean Quickly (§10) is about how fast the bike
            answers this single push.
          </p>
        </div>
    </section>

    <!-- 05 Braking & Trail-braking -->
    <section id="s-brake" class="py-9 border-b border-[var(--color-rule)] scroll-mt-16">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-2">
        <span class="label">Section 05</span><span class="tag">Expanded</span>
      </div>
      <h3 class="text-xl mb-4">Braking &amp; Trail-braking</h3>
      <div class="prose-manual">
          <p>
            We build the brakes on; we do not grab them. We start with light pressure, five
            percent or so, to load the front tyre and let it take the weight; then we squeeze
            on toward full pressure as the tyre digs in. A front tyre grabbed cold, before it
            is loaded, locks or washes out from under us.
          </p>
          <p>
            Trail-braking carries that brake past the turn-in point and bleeds it off as the
            lean comes on. We are trading one input for the other along the budget: as lean
            rises, brake pressure falls, and the sum stays pressed against the limit. This is
            the curved path across the friction circle in Fig. 2.1. Done well, there is no
            dead moment between braking and cornering: the front stays loaded, and the bike
            keeps turning all the way to the apex.
          </p>
        </div>
    </section>

    <!-- 06 Throttle -->
    <section id="s-throttle" class="py-9 border-b border-[var(--color-rule)] scroll-mt-16">
      <div class="label mb-2">Section 06</div>
      <h3 class="text-xl mb-4">Throttle</h3>
      <div class="prose-manual">
          <p>
            Throttle goes on smoothly, evenly, and in proportion to everything else we are
            doing, mainly lean and braking. We can still be quick about it: roll it on fast
            when we need to, as long as we roll it rather than snatch it. We never dump it.
          </p>
          <p>
            When the throttle is dumped, the front forks rebound and unload in an instant;
            this is one of the most common ways riders crash when they run wide. They get
            frightened. Already leaned over and braking, with little travel left in the forks,
            they snap the throttle shut, run out of travel, and lose the front.
          </p>
          <p>
            So when we run wide, we hold the throttle steady. A steady throttle still lets us
            slow down, and it lets us turn more, because a settled bike turns better than a
            lurching one.
          </p>
        </div>
    </section>

    <!-- 07 Gear Changes -->
    <section id="s-gears" class="py-9 border-b border-[var(--color-rule)] scroll-mt-16">
      <div class="label mb-2">Section 07</div>
      <h3 class="text-xl mb-4">Gear Changes</h3>
      <div class="prose-manual">
          <p>
            A gear change is one more input, so we keep it away from full lean. We do our
            downshifts while we are hard on the brakes, blipping down through the box as we
            slow. We save the upshift for the exit, as we pick the bike up and feed in
            throttle. At maximum lean, the gearbox stays untouched.
          </p>
        </div>
    </section>

    <!-- 08 Leaning -->
    <section id="s-lean" class="py-9 border-b border-[var(--color-rule)] scroll-mt-16">
      <div class="label mb-2">Section 08</div>
      <h3 class="text-xl mb-4">Leaning</h3>
      <div class="prose-manual">
          <p>
            Two angles matter here, and they are easy to confuse. The first is chassis lean:
            the angle of the bike itself against the ground. The second is system lean: the
            angle of a line drawn from the contact patch up to the combined centre of mass of
            bike and rider.
          </p>
          <p>
            We want to carry speed, so we want to keep chassis lean small. The steeper the
            bike leans, the smaller the contact patch; and a smaller patch is less grip to
            spend, in the same way that gearing the bike down trades drive for nothing we
            want here.
          </p>
          <p>
            We hold the bike more upright by moving the centre of mass to the inside of the
            turn. That lets the system lean as far as the corner demands while the chassis
            leans less. How we move that mass is the next section, Body Position (§09).
          </p>
        </div>
    </section>

    <!-- 09 Body Position -->
    <section id="s-body" class="py-9 border-b border-[var(--color-rule)] scroll-mt-16">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-2">
        <span class="label">Section 09</span><span class="tag">Draft</span>
      </div>
      <h3 class="text-xl mb-4">Body Position</h3>
      <div class="prose-manual">
          <p>
            Body position is how we keep the chassis upright while still turning hard. By
            hanging off to the inside, we shift the centre of mass of the whole system
            inboard; the bike then makes the same cornering force at a smaller chassis lean
            angle, and a smaller angle keeps a larger contact patch underneath us (§08).
          </p>
          <p>
            So we get our weight off the seat and to the inside: inside cheek off the seat,
            head and shoulder dropped down and into the corner, weight pressing through the
            inside peg. We carry that weight on our legs and core, not on our arms. The grip
            on the bars stays light; any tension in our arms runs straight into the steering,
            and it spoils the smooth brake and throttle inputs that everything else depends
            on.
          </p>
          <p class="editor">
            &#9998; This section was blank in your source notes; the above is a
            standard-technique draft for you to make your own. A lean-offset diagram will live
            here.
          </p>
        </div>
    </section>

    <!-- 10 Making the Bike Lean Quickly -->
    <section id="s-turnin" class="py-9 border-b border-[var(--color-rule)] scroll-mt-16">
      <div class="label mb-2">Section 10</div>
      <h3 class="text-xl mb-4">Making the Bike Lean Quickly</h3>
      <div class="prose-manual">
          <p>
            To flick the bike onto its side quickly, we want three things working for us.
            First, less gyroscopic resistance from the spinning masses: both the wheels and
            the engine fight a change of lean, so we roll off the throttle to settle the
            engine and brake hard to slow the wheels.
          </p>
          <p>
            Second, a steeper rake angle, the angle the steering makes with the road. A
            steeper angle gives the front wheel more leverage to counter-steer, and the bike
            answers faster; think of forcing a long bar against a short one, or pushing a door
            right beside its hinge. Third, a shorter wheelbase, which is the same leverage
            idea turned sideways: picture the bike as a rod joining the two contact patches,
            and a longer rod takes more force to swing.
          </p>
        </div>

      <Figure num="10.1" title="Turn-in Agility Factors"
        caption="A qualitative teaching model (not exact physics). Shed gyroscopic load and sharpen the geometry to see the turn-in index climb.">
        <LeanFactors client:visible />
      </Figure>
    </section>

    <!-- ══════════════════ PART III ══════════════════ -->
    <PartHeader
      id="p3" part="III" title="The Path"
      plate="III" plateTitle="The Racing Line"
      intro="Grip and inputs decide what the bike can do; the line decides where we do it. A good line straightens the corner. That means less lean for the same speed, and grip handed back to us for braking and drive."
    >
      <CornerDiagram mode="line" />
    </PartHeader>

    <!-- 11 Race Lines -->
    <section id="s-lines" class="py-9 border-b border-[var(--color-rule)] scroll-mt-16">
      <div class="label mb-2">Section 11</div>
      <h3 class="text-xl mb-4">Race Lines</h3>
      <div class="prose-manual">
          <p>
            The aim of a line is to straighten the corner as much as the track allows; a
            straighter path lets us carry more speed for the same lean. The apex is the point
            where we run closest to the inside of the turn.
          </p>
          <p>
            On the road, where we cannot see the whole corner at once, we hold to the outside
            until the exit opens into view; then we pick two or three points, the apex, the
            exit, and any others we need, and we join them into the line we aim at.
          </p>
        </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ══════════════════ PART IV ══════════════════ -->
    <PartHeader
      id="p4" part="IV" title="Putting It Together"
      plate="IV" plateTitle="Corner Phases"
      intro="Now we lay the inputs onto the line. A corner is one long handover: brakes to lean, then lean to throttle, run along the line we chose. At no point do we ask for more grip than the tyre has."
    >
      <CornerDiagram mode="zones" />
    </PartHeader>

    <!-- 12 Cornering -->
    <section id="s-corner" class="py-9 scroll-mt-16">
      <div class="label mb-2">Section 12</div>
      <h3 class="text-xl mb-4">Cornering: Entry, Apex, Exit</h3>
      <div class="prose-manual">
          <p>
            It helps to split a corner into three parts: the entry, the apex, and the exit.
            On entry we are off the throttle and hard on the brakes. From entry to apex we
            trade one for the other: brake pressure comes off as lean goes on.
          </p>
          <p>
            At the apex we are near full lean and almost off the brakes. Just before the
            brakes release fully, we take up the slack in the throttle, so there is never a
            moment where we ask the bike for nothing. From the apex to the exit we trade back
            the other way: lean comes off as the throttle comes on.
          </p>
        </div>

      <Figure num="12.1" title="The Input Handover"
        caption="Scrub the corner, or hit Run. Watch braking hand off to lean, then lean to throttle; the grip-used figure stays near 100% when the inputs overlap correctly, which is trail-braking (§05).">
        <CorneringPhases client:visible />
      </Figure>
    </section>
    </div>
  </main>
</Layout>

<style is:global>
  .editor {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.72rem;
    line-height: 1.6;
    color: var(--color-ink-faint);
    border-left: 2px solid var(--color-amber);
    padding-left: 0.7rem;
  }
</style>
